               <msContents>
                  <summary>The first of four volumes of the <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20476" change="#ids-cleanup">Kīmiyā-yi Saʻādat</title> (Alchemy of Happiness), together with <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6716"><idno>Persian MS 232</idno></ref>, <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6717">Persian MS 233</ref>, and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6718">Persian MS 233</ref>.  A major Persian work on religious obligations and moral duties by <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="person_31996761" role="aut" change="#role-assignment #ids-cleanup">Muḥammad al-Ghazzālī</persName>, considered one the greatest authorities of Shafi‘ī branch of Islamic law, known as <hi rend="italic"><addName key="person_31996761" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/31996761/" type="honorific">Hujjat al-Islam</addName></hi>, and author of about one hundred books and treatises mainly in Arabic as well as several in Persian, including the present work that he abridged and translated from his Arabic work <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc">Iḥyā’ ‘Ulūm al-Dīn</title> (Revival of the Religious Sciences).</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_231-item1">
                     <author key="person_31996761" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/31996761/" change="#ids-cleanup">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard" role="aut" change="#role-assignment">Ghazzālī, 1058-1111</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar" role="aut" change="#role-assignment">الغزالي</persName>
                     </author>
                     <editor key="person_f5107" role="scr" change="#role-assignment">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc">Ḥusayn bin Ḥasan <foreign xml:lang="ar">حسين بن حسن</foreign></persName> 
                     </editor>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20476" change="#ids-cleanup">Kīmiyā-yi saʻādat</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20476" change="#ids-cleanup">كيمياى سعادت</title>
                     <note>Volume I of IV. Unanimously written by the same hand.</note>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa" type="beginning">
                        شکر و سپاس فراوان بعدد ستارگان آسمان و قطره باران و برگ درختان و ریگ بیابان و ذره های زمین و آسمان مران خدایرا</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa">
                        اصل اول در اعتقاد اهل سنت است بدانکه هر که مسلمان شود اول واجب بر وی انست که کلمه های لا اله الا الله محمد رسول الله را که زبان گفت بدل بداند و باور کند</explicit>
                     <colophon></colophon>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl type="related">volume II <idno>Persian MS 232</idno>, volume III <idno>Persian MS 233</idno>, volume IV <idno>Persian MS 234</idno>

                           <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6716"><idno>Persian MS 232</idno></ref>, <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6717">Persian MS 233</ref>, and <ref target="https://www.fihrist.org.uk/catalog/manuscript_6718">Persian MS 233</ref>
                        </bibl>
                        <bibl>Lit: Ethe, IO 1781-1791; Rieu, BM 37; for several lithographs and modern prints see Mushar 2703-04.</bibl>
                     </listBibl>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Volume one, in 93 folios and 2 fly leaves, contain a general brief preface ff.lv-3v, an introduction on cognition, divided into four ‘unvān from 3v to 43r and the first rukn entitled ‘bādāt, divided into ten aṣl from f. 43r to f. 93r. </note>
